summary: Appointed Deputy Chief of Staff and Legislative Director Laney O’Shea, who previously led work on abortion policy for Congressman Jeff Jackson, indicating the office has senior staff experienced in abortion-related legislative work and oversight. Upon being sworn in, he explicitly pledged to "protect reproductive rights," reaffirming reproductive rights as a stated priority of his congressional agenda. The January 3, 2025 "Newest Members of Congress" release noted his swearing-in and reiterated that commitment.

Gill introduced the Respectful Treatment of Unborn Remains Act of 2025 (with Sen. Jim Banks) to prohibit abortion providers from disposing of fetal remains in publicly owned water systems, arguing the measure restores dignity to the unborn and citing public-health risks from medical-waste contamination. He used strong pro-life rhetoric—calling every life precious and describing disposal as 'disgusting and abhorrent'—referenced the Kermit Gosnell cases as an example, and backed criminal penalties for violating providers (fines and up to five years imprisonment) while excluding the pregnant woman. The bill was cosponsored by Reps. LaMalfa and Mary Miller and supported by groups such as SBA Pro-Life America, Priests for Life, and Students for Life Action.

Cosponsored the Women’s Health Protection Act to restore a nationwide right to access abortion care and the Right to Contraception Act; supports reproductive health protections and legislation to safeguard access to abortion, contraception, and related maternal protections (e.g., Stop Shackling and Detaining Pregnant Women Act).
